      <body>
          
         <div type="edition" xml:lang="pra-Latn">
           <p>  
            <lb n="1"/>pañcaṇha<unclear>ṃ</unclear> Arahanta
            <lb break="no" n="2"/>śatāṇaṃ Ayaṃ thūbho
          </p> 
         </div>
          
          
          
          
         <div type="apparatus">
           
               <listApp>
                  <app loc="1">
                     <lem>pañcaṇha<unclear>ṃ</unclear></lem>
                     <rdg source="bib:Gokhale1991_01">paceṇha</rdg>
                     <note>This Gen. Pl. ending is attested in AMg, cf. Pischel § 440. As stressed by Pischel § 246, <foreign>-ṇh-</foreign> perhaps arose from a confusion between <foreign>-ṇṇ-</foreign> and <foreign>-h-</foreign> &lt; <foreign>-s-</foreign> from the pronominal genitive plural ending in -<foreign>saṃ</foreign>. See also Norman 1992: 201.<!-- this needs to be added to Zotero --></note> 
                  </app>
                  <app loc="2"> 
                     <lem>Arahanta<lb break="no" n="2"/>śatāṇaṃ&gt;</lem>
                     <rdg source="bib:Gokhale1991_01">Arahant<unclear>ā</unclear>gratāṇaṁ</rdg> 
                     <note>Compare III Bhaj 11 which according to my new edition reads <foreign>paṃca<unclear>n</unclear>naṁ vasibhūtasatānaṁ thū<unclear>po</unclear></foreign>. The <foreign>-po</foreign> in III Bhaj 11 is engraved below the base-line, due to an irregularity of the stone.</note> 
                  </app>
               </listApp>
         </div>
          
          
          
          
          
         <div type="translation">
 	<p>This is the stūpa of the five hundred Arahants.</p>
         </div>
          
          
          
          
         <div type="commentary">
      <p>Compare Gokhale’s translation: “The stupa was erected in the honour of ‘Ārya’ was the best ‘arhat’ every day.</p>      
         </div>
          
          
          
          
